<!-- ═══ Context ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="context" style="margin-top: 40px;">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Context</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">ACCUPASS is Taiwan's leading event platform, helping organizers create event pages, manage registrations and ticketing, while also serving as a discovery platform for attendees.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I joined ACCUPASS as a UX Designer, responsible for interface design across the Event Editor, Organizer Dashboard, and Sponsor Project. I later transitioned to Design Lead, managing a team of one UI Designer and two Graphic Designers.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Over those two years, I identified a fundamental problem: ACCUPASS had no clear brand strategy. Whether in marketing materials, UI design, or sales communications, everyone interpreted the brand through their own lens. The only shared touchpoint was a mascot. This created three compounding issues:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <ul class="body-text issue-list">
            <li><strong>Marketing materials were visually inconsistent</strong> — each campaign felt like a different brand</li>
            <li><strong>UI design lacked brand grounding</strong> — color and visual tone were left to individual designer judgment</li>
            <li><strong>Sales had no unified messaging</strong> — the brand identity was vague to the outside world</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The issue was first raised by a colleague in marketing. Around the same time, Mailchimp published their famous Voice and Tone brand guide — and it clicked: we needed to build something equivalent for ACCUPASS.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">My Role</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">As Design Lead, I decided to initiate and own this project. My role went beyond design execution — I was the driver of the entire rebranding process, from methodology design to cross-functional alignment to final guideline delivery.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ The Spark ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="the-spark">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>The Spark — Bridge of Spies</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Before formally launching the project, I needed the team to viscerally understand why this mattered.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I opened with a video clip. When Tom Hanks's film Bridge of Spies was released, he appeared on The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon for a segment called "Kid Theater." Jimmy Fallon had a group of kids — who had only been told the movie's title — imagine what the film was about and perform their own version of the story. Each child came up with something completely different, because all they had was a name. No core concept. No guiding narrative.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block image-block--center">
        <img src="/images/accupass/bridge-of-spies.webp" alt="The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon — Kid Theater with Tom Hanks" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">《The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon》「Kid Theater with Tom Hanks」</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I told the team: this is exactly where we are right now.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">1. We have a name — ACCUPASS — but no brand core.<br>2. Our brand is being interpreted by others, not defined and communicated by us.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Just like those kids filling in the blanks with their own imagination, everyone in the company — marketing, design, sales — had their own version of what ACCUPASS was. None of them were wrong. But none of them were the same.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The analogy landed. It created the shared sense of urgency we needed to officially kick off the rebranding.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ From Scattered Keywords to a Brand Persona ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="keywords">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>From Scattered Keywords to a Brand Persona</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">With no existing playbook to follow, I designed a bottom-up brand discovery process. The core principle: brand identity shouldn't be defined behind closed doors by the design team — it should reflect the collective consciousness of the whole company.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">We ran the project in weekly cycles, aligned to the Design Team's existing Weekly Meeting cadence, over approximately four weeks.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 1 — Kickoff &amp; Alignment</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Synced with the marketing team first, framing the project scope and inviting them as core collaborators.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 2 — Company-Wide Keyword Interviews</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block image-block--center">
        <img src="/images/accupass/keyword-interviews.webp" alt="Asking colleagues how they imagine ACCUPASS" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">Asking our colleagues how do they imagine ACCUPASS</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">During the Friday afternoon tea break — a regular company ritual — I conducted informal interviews with every ACCUPASS employee:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <blockquote class="brand-quote">"What image do you think ACCUPASS projects? What feeling should it create? What keywords come to mind when you think of ACCUPASS?"</blockquote>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The goal wasn't just to gather input for external-facing design. It was to build collective ownership — so that every person felt they were a part of shaping the brand, not just receiving it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 3 — Keyword Sorting &amp; Classification</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block image-block--center">
        <img src="/images/accupass/keyword-sorting.webp" alt="Organized all collected keywords into three dimensions" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">Organized all collected keywords into three dimensions</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The design team organized all collected keywords into three dimensions:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <ul class="body-text issue-list">
            <li><strong>Personality:</strong> the brand's inner character</li>
            <li><strong>Expression:</strong> first impressions, visual and tonal qualities</li>
            <li><strong>Behavior:</strong> how the brand acts and interacts</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 4 — Brand Personification</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">We used the prompt "If ACCUPASS were a person…" to converge the keywords. Each design team member independently drafted their own personified description using the classified keywords. We then merged and synthesized these into a single unified brand persona.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/accupass/brand-persona.webp" alt="Brand persona synthesized from keywords" class="rounded-image">
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 5 — Cross-Team Alignment &amp; Sign-Off</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Presented the synthesized brand persona to the Marketing Head for validation. This step was critical — it ensured the brand definition wasn't just a design team deliverable, but a cross-functional consensus.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Phase 6 — Translating to Application</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">With the brand direction confirmed, we shifted into application mode: how do the persona's traits, behaviors, and image translate concretely into UI and graphic design? This became the foundation for the full design guidelines.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Design Application ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="design-application">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Design Application</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The challenge now was making abstract qualities — adventurous, passionate, inspired — into concrete rules that designers and engineers could actually execute.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Color System</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Established a primary color standard and extended it into two supporting color systems for different contexts. Color choices were no longer arbitrary — every decision had a brand rationale behind it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/accupass/color-system.webp" alt="ACCUPASS color system" class="rounded-image">
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Consumer Side — "Millennia of Tradition, a Brand New Experience"</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Redesigned the default user avatars around the concept of "little monsters exploring the event universe." These characters embody the brand's adventurous and playful personality — new users experience the brand tone from the very first moment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="avatar-row">
            <img src="/images/accupass/user-5.webp" alt="User avatar" class="avatar-item avatar-item--rounded">
            <img src="/images/accupass/user-1.webp" alt="User avatar" class="avatar-item avatar-item--rounded">
            <img src="/images/accupass/user-2.webp" alt="User avatar" class="avatar-item avatar-item--rounded">
            <img src="/images/accupass/user-3.webp" alt="User avatar" class="avatar-item avatar-item--rounded">
            <img src="/images/accupass/user-4.webp" alt="User avatar" class="avatar-item avatar-item--rounded">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Organizer Side — "Flexible and Adaptable"</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Designed organizer avatars as variations of a door motif, symbolizing the partnership relationship — every door opening into a new event possibility. A slightly differentiated color palette maintains the lively atmosphere while giving the organizer-facing experience its own sense of professionalism.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="avatar-row">
            <img src="/images/accupass/host-purple.webp" alt="Organizer avatar" class="avatar-item">
            <img src="/images/accupass/host-castle.webp" alt="Organizer avatar" class="avatar-item">
            <img src="/images/accupass/host-green.webp" alt="Organizer avatar" class="avatar-item">
            <img src="/images/accupass/host-orange.webp" alt="Organizer avatar" class="avatar-item">
            <img src="/images/accupass/host-pink.webp" alt="Organizer avatar" class="avatar-item">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Empty States — "No Empty Moments"</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Added brand illustrations to every empty state screen, ensuring users never encounter a cold blank page at any point in their journey. The brand's warmth persists even in the absence of content.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="avatar-row avatar-row--centered">
            <img src="/images/accupass/empty-live.webp" alt="Empty state — Live" class="avatar-item avatar-item--circle">
            <img src="/images/accupass/empty-me.webp" alt="Empty state — Me" class="avatar-item avatar-item--circle">
            <img src="/images/accupass/empty-like.webp" alt="Empty state — Like" class="avatar-item avatar-item--circle">
            <img src="/images/accupass/empty-login.webp" alt="Empty state — Login" class="avatar-item avatar-item--circle">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Brand Guidelines Document</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Produced a comprehensive Guideline covering UI design, marketing materials, and event visual applications — enabling non-designers to create in alignment with the brand spirit without needing to consult the design team each time.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Core Design Challenges ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="core-challenges">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Core Design Challenges</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Challenge A: No Playbook — Designing the Rebranding Process Itself</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The biggest challenge wasn't figuring out what the brand should look like. It was figuring out how to lead a group of people toward an answer together. There weren't many rebranding methodologies to reference at the time, and we were working within a flat, headcount-heavy organization — I needed an approach that was inclusive enough for everyone to participate, but structured enough to actually converge.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The "keywords → three-dimension classification → personification" pathway worked because its entry barrier was low (anyone can contribute a keyword) while its convergence mechanism was clear (the classification framework + the personification prompt gave the scattered input a shape).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="two-col-images">
            <img src="/images/accupass/challenge-a-1.webp" alt="Keyword classification process" class="rounded-image">
            <img src="/images/accupass/challenge-a-2.webp" alt="Brand personification workshop" class="rounded-image">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Challenge B: From Divergence to Convergence — Synthesizing a Whole Company's Ideas</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The flat team structure made communication frictionless — we had regular Friday tea breaks and open demo sessions, so there were no organizational barriers to getting input. But synthesizing dozens of people's divergent ideas into an actionable, coherent set of guidelines was still genuinely hard work.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">What helped was that the design team itself was complementary: when I got stuck, someone else would pick it up and push forward. It was a genuinely collaborative process, not just me driving it alone.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block image-block--center">
        <img src="/images/accupass/challenge-b.webp" alt="Discuss with design team" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">Discuss with design team</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Challenge C: Evangelizing Brand to Non-Designers</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Brand concepts are inherently abstract. Once the guidelines existed, the next challenge was making sure engineers understood why a color was used a certain way, and that marketing could intuitively judge whether a piece of creative was on-brand.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">We used a two-track approach:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <ul class="body-text issue-list">
            <li><strong>Direct conversation:</strong> talked through the reasoning behind each guideline with engineers and marketers — not just handing them a document, but explaining where the rules came from and why they mattered</li>
            <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> the Brand Guidelines served as a persistent reference, structured so that anyone reading it could understand the brand's origins, not just its outputs</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ UX Research ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="ux-research">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>UX Research: Organizer App Pain Point Study</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Alongside the rebranding work, I initiated a user research study focused on the Organizer App — building an evidence base for the product experience layer in parallel with the brand layer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Methods:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <ul class="body-text issue-list">
            <li><strong>Pain point interviews:</strong> in-depth interviews with event organizers to understand the core friction points they experienced managing events in the app</li>
            <li><strong>User Journey Map:</strong> synthesized interview findings into a journey map, visualizing pain points and opportunity areas across the full event management workflow</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/accupass/user-journey-map.webp" alt="User Journey Map" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">User Journey Map</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The outputs were intended as a foundation for subsequent app development. Although the team was downsized before the full roadmap could be executed, the research established a "ground truth" for the organizer experience — any future design decisions about the Organizer App would have user evidence to reference rather than relying on assumptions.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Impact & Learnings ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="impact">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Impact &amp; Learnings</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Brand Alignment</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Built a brand persona definition from zero in four weeks. The design team went from everyone having their own interpretation to having a shared, articulate foundation — clear rules for color usage, visual semantics, and tone of voice that everyone could point to.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Cross-Department Ownership</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Because the entire company participated in the keyword interviews, the brand didn't feel like something the design team imposed. Marketing, sales, and engineering all had a hand in shaping it — which made adoption and buy-in significantly easier.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Reusable Design Asset</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The brand persona definition, color system, avatar systems, empty state illustrations, and brand guidelines became a lasting design asset for the team to build on.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Reflection ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="reflection">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Reflection: What I'd Do Differently</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Quantify the brand chaos earlier. The project was cut short when the team was unexpectedly downsized, leaving the guidelines only partially applied to external touchpoints. Looking back, if I had quantified the cost of brand inconsistency upfront — marketing asset rework rates, user perception surveys — I would have had a much stronger ROI argument when resources came into question. The key lesson: in resource-constrained environments, the earlier a design initiative can demonstrate measurable value, the more defensible it becomes when priorities shift.</p>
    </div>
</div>
